{"title_page": "Albertinum", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n|name = Albertinum\n|image = AlbertinumDresden.jpg\n|caption =\n|image_upright =\n|pushpin_map =\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.051944|13.744444|display=inline}}\n|established = 1887\n|dissolved =\n|location = Georg-Treu-Platz 2,<br />01067 Dresden, Germany\n|type = [[Art museum]], [[Historic site]]\n|visitors =\n|director =\n|curator =\n|publictransit =\n|website =\n}}\n[[File:Upper sculpture hall, Albertinum, Dresden.jpg|thumb|300px|Upper sculpture hall, Albertinum, Dresden]]\nThe '''Albertinum''' ({{IPA-de|alb\u025b\u0281\u02c8ti\u02d0n\u028am}}) is a modern art museum. The sandstone-clad [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival]] building is located on [[Br\u00fchl's Terrace]] in the historic center of [[Dresden]], Germany. It is named after King [[Albert of Saxony]].\n\nThe Albertinum hosts the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') and the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]] (''Skulpturensammlung'') of the [[Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden|Dresden State Art Collections]]. The museum presents both paintings and sculptures from [[Romanticism]] to the present, covering a period of some 200 years.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dresden Albertinum Ostportal.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|The eastside portal of the Albertinum]]\n\nThe Albertinum was built between 1884 and 1887 by extending a former armoury, or arsenal, that had been constructed between 1559 and 1563 at the same location.<ref name=\"Loeffler\" >Fritz L\u00f6ffler: ''Das alte Dresden - Geschichte seiner Bauten''. 16th ed. Leipzig: Seemann, 2006, {{ISBN|978-3-86502-000-0}} {{in lang|de}}</ref> The new building was designed by the regional master builder Carl Adolf Canzler in the Renaissance Revival style to house the royal \"Collection of Antique and Modern Sculptures\".<ref name=\"Loeffler\" /> The building was named after the Saxonian King [[Albert of Saxony|Albert]] who reigned at the time. In 1889, the Sculpture Collection was moved in and has since remained there.\n\nDamaged in the February 13, 1945 [[bombing of Dresden in World War II]], the Albertinum was restored by 1953.<ref name=\"Loeffler\" />\n\nBesides the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]], the Albertinum has housed the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') in the upper rooms since 1965. It was also the temporary postwar home of the [[M\u00fcnzkabinett|Numismatic Cabinet]] (''M\u00fcnzkabinett'') and the [[Green Vault]] (''Gr\u00fcnes Gew\u00f6lbe'') until the exhibitions were moved to the rebuilt [[Dresden Castle]] in 2002 and 2004, respectively.\n\nThe [[2002 European floods|floods of 2002]] necessitated renovating the Albertinum and building a new flood-proof depository. After closing in 2006, the building was finally reopened on June 20, 2010 as a \"house of the modern\" with the New Masters Gallery and the Sculpture Collection, \"designed for encounters between painting and sculpture, between the Romantic and the Modern\".<ref name=state>{{cite web |url=http://www.skd.museum/en/museums-institutions/albertinum/index.html |title=Albertinum. Art from Romanticism to the Present |year=2011 |accessdate=7 December 2011 |publisher=Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203090959/http://www.skd.museum/en/museums-institutions/albertinum/index.html |archive-date=2011-12-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The most important improvement has been the roofing of the inner courtyard to form an [[Atrium (architecture)|atrium]], called \"an ark for the art\". Furthermore, the glazed walling of the establishment's depositories gives visitors views of the inner workings of a museum.\n\n== Museums ==\n[[File:The Albertinum with Frauenkirche behind.jpg|thumb|300px|The Albertinum with Frauenkirche behind]]\n[[File:Sculpture corridor in the Albertinum in Dresden.jpg|thumb|300px|Sculpture corridor in the Albertinum in Dresden]]\n[[File:Albertinum Lichthof.jpg|thumb|300px|The central atrium of the Albertinum]]\n\nThe Albertinum houses the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') and the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]] (''Skulpturensammlung''). The holdings of the two museums, with paintings ranging from [[Caspar David Friedrich]] to [[Adrian Ludwig Richter|Ludwig Richter]] and sculptures from [[Auguste Rodin]] to the 21st century, are displayed on three floors in exhibition halls with a modern look.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of museums in Saxony]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons-inline|Category:Albertinum|Albertinum}}\n* [https://albertinum.skd.museum/en/ Albertinum Homepage] of [[Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden|Dresden State Art Collections]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Dresden]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Dresden]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildings and structures in Dresden]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1889]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Museum\n|name = Albertinum\n|image = AlbertinumDresden.jpg\n|caption =\n|image_upright =\n|pushpin_map =\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.051944|13.744444|display=inline}}\n|established = 1887\n|dissolved =\n|location = Georg-Treu-Platz 2,<br />01067 Dresden, Germany\n|type = [[Art museum]], [[Historic site]]\n|visitors =\n|director =\n|curator =\n|publictransit =\n|website =\n}}\n[[File:Upper sculpture hall, Albertinum, Dresden.jpg|thumb|300px|Upper sculpture hall, Albertinum, Dresden]]\nThe '''Albertinum''' ({{IPA-de|alb\u025b\u0281\u02c8ti\u02d0n\u028am}}) is a modern art museum. The sandstone-clad [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival]] building is located on [[Br\u00fchl's Terrace]] in the historic center of [[Dresden]], Germany. It is named after King [[Albert of Saxony]].\n\nThe Albertinum hosts the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') and the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]] (''Skulpturensammlung'') of the [[Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden|Dresden State Art Collections]]. The museum presents both paintings and sculptures from [[Romanticism]] to the present, covering a period of some 200 years.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dresden Albertinum Ostportal.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|The eastside portal of the Albertinum]]\n\nThe Albertinum was built between 1884 and 1887 by extending a former armoury, or arsenal, that had been constructed between 1559 and 1563 at the same location.<ref name=\"Loeffler\" >Fritz L\u00f6ffler: ''Das alte Dresden - Geschichte seiner Bauten''. 16th ed. Leipzig: Seemann, 2006, {{ISBN|978-3-86502-000-0}} {{in lang|de}}</ref> The new building was designed by the regional master builder Carl Adolf Canzler in the Renaissance Revival style to house the royal \"Collection of Antique and Modern Sculptures\".<ref name=\"Loeffler\" /> The building was named after the Saxonian King [[Albert of Saxony|Albert]] who reigned at the time. In 1889, the Sculpture Collection was moved in and has since remained there. \n\nDamaged in the February 13, 1945 [[bombing of Dresden in World War II]], the Albertinum was restored by 1953.<ref name=\"Loeffler\" /> \n\nBesides the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]], the Albertinum has housed the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') in the upper rooms since 1965. It was also the temporary postwar home of the [[M\u00fcnzkabinett|Numismatic Cabinet]] (''M\u00fcnzkabinett'') and the [[Green Vault]] (''Gr\u00fcnes Gew\u00f6lbe'') until the exhibitions were moved to the rebuilt [[Dresden Castle]] in 2002 and 2004, respectively.\n\nThe [[2002 European floods|floods of 2002]] necessitated renovating the Albertinum and building a new flood-proof depository. After closing in 2006, the building was finally reopened on June 20, 2010 as a \"house of the modern\" with the New Masters Gallery and the Sculpture Collection, \"designed for encounters between painting and sculpture, between the Romantic and the Modern\".<ref name=state>{{cite web |url=http://www.skd.museum/en/museums-institutions/albertinum/index.html |title=Albertinum. Art from Romanticism to the Present |year=2011 |accessdate=7 December 2011 |publisher=Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203090959/http://www.skd.museum/en/museums-institutions/albertinum/index.html |archive-date=2011-12-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The most important improvement has been the roofing of the inner courtyard to form an [[Atrium (architecture)|atrium]], called \"an ark for the art\". Furthermore, the glazed walling of the establishment's depositories gives visitors views of the inner workings of a museum.\n\n== Museums ==\n[[File:The Albertinum with Frauenkirche behind.jpg|thumb|300px|The Albertinum with Frauenkirche behind]]\n[[File:Sculpture corridor in the Albertinum in Dresden.jpg|thumb|300px|Sculpture corridor in the Albertinum in Dresden]]\n[[File:Albertinum Lichthof.jpg|thumb|300px|The central atrium of the Albertinum]]\n\nThe Albertinum houses the [[Galerie Neue Meister|New Masters Gallery]] (''Galerie Neue Meister'') and the [[Skulpturensammlung|Sculpture Collection]] (''Skulpturensammlung''). The holdings of the two museums, with paintings ranging from [[Caspar David Friedrich]] to [[Adrian Ludwig Richter|Ludwig Richter]] and sculptures from [[Auguste Rodin]] to the 21st century, are displayed on three floors in exhibition halls with a modern look.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of museums in Saxony]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons-inline|Category:Albertinum|Albertinum}}\n* [https://albertinum.skd.museum/en/ Albertinum Homepage] of [[Staatliche Kunstsammlungen Dresden|Dresden State Art Collections]]\n\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Dresden]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Dresden]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildin